Take it easy policy", "entities": {"description": {}}}, "isAutomated": false, "automatedBy": null}, "extendedEntities": {}, "card": null, "place": {}, "entities": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [], "timestamps": [], "urls": [], "user_mentions": []}, "quoted_tweet": {"type": "tweet", "id": "2051236792360218688", "url": "https://x.com/brahma_4u/status/2051236792360218688", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/brahma_4u/status/2051236792360218688", "text": "Mahindra sold more tractors in North America last year than John Deere sold in India by a factor of about 6. \n\nThe Mahindra 1626 is now the best-selling sub-compact tractor in the US under 30 HP, and most of the buyers have no idea it's Indian.\n\nThe trick was simple and slightly unfair. \n\nMahindra figured out in the early 2000s that the American hobby-farm and acreage-owner segment five acres, a horse, a fence to fix was being ignored by Deere and Kubota, who were optimizing for 200 HP row-crop machines with $80k price tags. \n\nMahindra walked in with a 26 HP diesel built in Nagpur, sold it for $13k through tractor dealers in Texas and Tennessee, and quietly took the bottom of the market. \n\nThe Nagpur plant ships about 50,000 units a year to North America now. Deere's India JV with TAFE shipped its last tractor in 2024 and folded.\n\nThe lesson isn't that India makes cheap tractors.\n\n It's that the global tractor market had a 30 HP hole in it for two decades and an Indian company was the only one paying attention.\n\n@anandmahindra", "source": "Twitter for iPhone", "retweetCount": 184, "replyCount": 31, "likeCount": 1417, "quoteCount": 11, "viewCount": 61983, "createdAt": "Mon May 04 09:45:36 +0000 2026", "lang": "en", "bookmarkCount": 201, "isReply": false, "inReplyToId": null, "conversationId": "2051236792360218688", "displayTextRange": [0, 279], "inReplyToUserId": null, "inReplyToUsername": null, "author": {"type": "user", "userName": "brahma_4u", "url": "https://x.com/brahma_4u", "twitterUrl": "https://twi